<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-area-of-rhombuses" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Area of Rhombuses</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_akqv02su">
            <p xml:id="auto_iznffyqz">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_o73v9xnw">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_e3061w3i">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_kr6aem3f">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_hcsbudsi">
                        2.5 Area of Polygons
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5mc01ksm">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_qdtw2pf8">
                        <ul>
                            <li xml:id="auto_dhsv10br">
                                <p xml:id="auto_d7johsu9">
                                    Determine the area of quadrilaterals in different situations. 
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_phm4nql0">
                                <p xml:id="auto_dfleloim">
                                    Explore the area of polygons as used in real-life situations.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                        
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_9op6r338" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_lnon8b6v">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_tcsykatj" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_4d0zf1ze">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_h0tj2h7d" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_yyxarhsp"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_h5q56nyo">
                        <p xml:id="auto_cm1ctmxx">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define a rhombus as an equilateral quadrilateral with all sides equal. State the properties: opposite angles are equal, diagonals bisect each other at right angles, diagonals bisect the interior angles. State the area formula: <m>\text{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \times d_1 \times d_2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_79ll1n0s">
                        <p xml:id="auto_m4ffn3ve">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate the area of rhombuses using the diagonal formula.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_bm4kqkvk">
                        <p xml:id="auto_qtgq0z36">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world problems involving areas of rhombuses (tiles, logos, road signs). Apply the Pythagorean theorem to find side lengths of rhombuses.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_uo3ao7rb">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-polygons/area-of-rhombuses.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_fixaa5wj">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-polygons/step-by-step-guide_area-of-rhombuses.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Exploring Properties of a Rhombus</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_d53az9j4">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_ozvfjp5s">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_q47tl1wi">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_9kv00m76">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_n950ns7f">
                    Groups of 2–3 students
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_ugjvmpy3">
                <title>Setup</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_bsw9muo1">
                    Distribute rulers, protractors, pencils, graph paper, scissors, and string or thread. Students will draw a rhombus, measure its properties, and discover that the diagonals bisect each other at <m>90°</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_35rf7ex0">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_ke7e8hxj">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_pecnwsrv">
                            <p xml:id="auto_oa5m39n2">
                                Circulate among groups, ensuring students understand how to draw a rhombus with all sides equal.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_3zxpl7lq">
                            <p xml:id="auto_rfkk2w1y">
                                Ask probing questions: <q>What do you notice about the opposite angles?</q>, <q>How do the diagonals intersect?</q>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_mr4do20x">
                            <p xml:id="auto_16bzfwiy">
                                For struggling groups: <q>Let us draw the rhombus together. All four sides must be equal.</q>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_rqdszre0">
                            <p xml:id="auto_haobd8iq">
                                For early finishers: <q>Can you find a formula for the area of a rhombus using the diagonals?</q>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_pu5n1f9c">
                            <p xml:id="auto_j68hnhnt">
                                Guide students to articulate: <q>The diagonals bisect each other at <m>90°</m>.</q>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_9ee07olj">
                            <p xml:id="auto_4dqvcpcn">
                                Identify 2–3 groups with clear observations to share with the class.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>


        <activity xml:id="auto_dmibe17w">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_duqu8lm3">
                    <m>\textbf{Materials Needed:}</m>
                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ge3ss0vj"> Ruler, Protractor, Pencil, Graph paper, Scissors (optional) and String or thread (optional)
                    </p>
                    <sidebyside>
                    <p xml:id="auto_gbdjvn4e">
                        <ul xml:id="auto_cgflom4v">
                            <li xml:id="auto_6l0scdx8">
                                <p xml:id="auto_0yuxz0ls">
                                   Draw a Rhombus Using a ruler, draw a quadrilateral with all sides equal in length. Make sure the opposite angles are equal. Label the vertices as A, B, C, D in order.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_gmglstah">
                                <p xml:id="auto_q619c2u9">
                                    Measure the Sides using a ruler to confirm that all four sides are of equal length.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_0f0oe7m6">
                                <p xml:id="auto_2xpn19d8">
                                    Measure the angles using a protractor to measure each of the interior angles. Observe: Opposite angles should be equal.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_ba041pkf">
                                 <p xml:id="auto_5k22aj5f">
                                    Draw the Diagonals:
                                    </p>
                                    <p xml:id="auto_wdvyo1zb">
                                        Draw diagonal AC and diagonal BD.
                                    </p>
                                        <p xml:id="auto_eet4inh2">
                                        Measure their lengths and angles at the intersection point.
                                    </p>
                                    <p xml:id="auto_dgkjytvl">
                                        Observe: Diagonals bisect each other at 90°, and they are not equal.
                                                                   
                                    
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_wzu3dps7">
                                <p xml:id="auto_dlwrtbli">
                                    Cut and Fold (Optional):
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_mippyzhu">
                                    Cut out the rhombus and fold it along both diagonals.
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_bltdtd7w">
                                    Observe the symmetry and how the diagonals act as lines of symmetry.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                    <image source="rhombus-pic.png">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>
                    </sidebyside>
                    <p xml:id="auto_4im105y9">
                        <m>\textbf{Discussion Questions}</m>
                        <ol xml:id="auto_5tdrujgt">
                            <li xml:id="auto_5ing3nli">
                                <p xml:id="auto_ujfe9v9y">
                                    What do you notice about the sides and angles of the rhombus?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_8ecc9c59">
                                <p xml:id="auto_xx4tstnf">
                                    How do the diagonals interact with each other?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_xw4ssce1">
                                <p xml:id="auto_nz1yefbp">
                                    What makes a rhombus different from a square or a general parallelogram?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>


    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_g7wly17x">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_psfd7twb">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_r6n43f5r">
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_jd81h3zt">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_6lc603v3">
                    To formalise the area formula for rhombuses: <m>\text{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \times d_1 \times d_2</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Scaffolding Strategies</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_lchto26t">
                Address common misconceptions:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_9kh1zkhq">
                <ul>
                    <li xml:id="auto_05t83xco">
                        <p xml:id="auto_g99lg1lh">
                            <alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>I can use the side length to find the area directly.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> You need the diagonals to use the formula <m>\text{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \times d_1 \times d_2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_t10xk8mh">
                        <p xml:id="auto_3yya18rd">
                            <alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>The diagonals are equal.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> In a rhombus the diagonals are not equal unless it is a square.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_1ad4rh4a">
                        <p xml:id="auto_w8ji1c3o">
                            <alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>I need to know all four sides to find the area.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> You only need the two diagonals.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_w8gbjswc">
                        <p xml:id="auto_vtrsmgyn">
                            <alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>The area formula is the same as a parallelogram.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> For a rhombus we use the diagonals: <m>\text{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \times d_1 \times d_2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>


        <insight xml:id="auto_f876cqt1">
            <p xml:id="auto_paqw9mnv">
                A <m>\textbf{rhombus}</m> is an equilateral quadrilateral. All its sides are of <m>\textbf{equal length}</m>, vut all it's angles are not. All its sides are equal and the diagnols bisect at <m>90 ^\circ</m>. Which other quadrilateral has all its sides equal?
            </p>
            <image>
            <latex-image label="rhombus-figure">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Define the coordinates of the rhombus
                    \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (B) at (3.5,1.5);
                    \coordinate (C) at (3,5);
                    \coordinate (D) at (-0.5,3.5);

                    % Draw the rhombus
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Mark equal sides with double dashes extending inside
                    \draw[thick] (2,0.75) --++(0.3,0) --++(-0.6,0);
                    \draw[thick] (3.5,3.25) --++(0.3,0.3) --++(-0.6,-0.6);
                    \draw[thick] (1,4.25) --++(-0.3,0.3) --++(0.6,-0.6);
                    \draw[thick] (-0.5,1.75) --++(-0.3,-0.3) --++(0.6,0.6);
                    
                    % Add labels for vertices
                    \node[below left] at (A) {A};
                    \node[below right] at (B) {B};
                    \node[above right] at (C) {C};
                    \node[above left] at (D) {D};
                    
                    % Add label for equal sides
                    \node[left] at (0,0.5) {\small \textit{all sides the same}};
                    \draw[-&gt;] (-1,0.5) -- (0,1);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
            <p xml:id="auto_qe6uic04">
                Compare the rhombus with the rectangle below.
            </p>
            <image >
            <latex-image label="rectangle-figure">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Define the coordinates of the rectangle (doubled in size)
                    \coordinate (A) at (-9.0,0);
                    \coordinate (B) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (C) at (0,6);
                    \coordinate (D) at (-9.0,6);

                    % Draw the rectangle
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Mark right angles at the corners (scaled up)
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- ++(1,0) -- ++(0,1) -- ++(-1,0);
                    \draw[thick] (B) -- ++(-1,0) -- ++(0,1) -- ++(1,0);
                    \draw[thick] (C) -- ++(-1,0) -- ++(0, -1) -- ++(1,0);
                    \draw[thick] (D) -- ++(1,0) -- ++(0,-1) -- ++(-1,0);
                    
                    % Add label for angles (positioned below the rectangle)
                    \node[below] at (-7,-1) {\huge \textit{all angles the same}};
                    \draw[-&gt;] (-6,-0.8) -- (-8.5,0.6);
                    
                    % Add txt description (adjusted positioning)
                    \node[right] at (-7,-4) {\huge \textit{\textbf{Equiangular}}};
                    \node[right] at (-8,-5) {\huge \textit{- A rectangle is an equiangular quadrilateral.}};
                    \node[right] at (-8,-6) {\huge \textit{-Its angles are all equal, but not all}};
                    \node[right] at (-8,-7) {\huge \textit{ its sides are equal.}};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Area of a Rhombus</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_xpbseafw">
                    For a Rhombus with diagonals <m>d_1</m> and <m>d_2</m>, we have: <md>
                        \text{Area} = \tfrac{1}{2} \times d_1 \times d_2 </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_3i79az79">
                    We can also find the area using the side length <m>s</m> and the perpendicular height <m>h</m>: <md>
                        \text{Area} = s \times h
                    </md>
                    
                </p>
            </paragraphs>
            <p xml:id="auto_mzdcws4h">
                <m>\textbf{ Properties of a Rhombus}</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_9was9ig1">
                <ul xml:id="auto_jn8ckbhc">
                    <li xml:id="auto_n6948r8u">
                        <p xml:id="auto_fvli4w78">
                            All sides are equal in length. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_xyudhvdx">
                        <p xml:id="auto_35g3znwn">
                            Opposite angles are equal.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_5ocqsjeq">
                        <p xml:id="auto_8y7sjcv8">
                            Diagonals bisect each other at right angles. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_b8k1iye9">
                            <p xml:id="auto_1fwuwi5h">
                                Diagonals bisect the interior angles.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_zzlhl5j8">
                            <p xml:id="auto_yopxsb0e">
                                Some examples of a rhombus are Tiles or patterns in flooring, or The shape of playing cards (diamonds suit).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </insight>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_6ov4ol0i">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_vqrk3vu3">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_jeuepx0w">
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_n2zdo99e">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_g8zetj4g">
                    Students apply the rhombus area formula and the Pythagorean theorem to find areas and side lengths.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_5en10nf3">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_x15aa3yu">
                    Work through the first example on the board, modelling how to apply the diagonal formula and how to use the Pythagorean theorem to find the side length. Then direct students to attempt the second example independently. Circulate to support learners who struggle with the trigonometric step.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    
    <example xml:id="auto_e2i4u1xn">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_ado14izm">
                A rhombus has a diagonal of 10 cm and another diagonal of 24 cm. Find:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_oopui6r8">
            i) The area of the rhombus.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_chath4cl">
              ii).The length of one side of the rhombus.
            </p>

    <image width="50%">
    <latex-image label="rhombus">
        \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Define the rhombus vertices
            \coordinate (A) at (0,3);
            \coordinate (B) at (3,0);
            \coordinate (C) at (0,-3);
            \coordinate (D) at (-3,0);
            % Draw the rhombus with thick pink outline
            \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;

            % Draw diagonals with dashed lines
            \draw[dashed] (A) -- (C);
            \draw[dashed] (B) -- (D);

            % Mark right angles at the intersection of diagonals
            \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
            \draw[thick] (O) ++(0.2,0) -- ++(0,0.2) -- ++(-0.2,0);

            % Label the vertices
            \node[above] at (A) {A};
            \node[right] at (B) {B};
            \node[below] at (C) {C};
            \node[left] at (D) {D};
            \node[below right] at (O) {O};
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
    </image>
           
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_ljy21i0e">
                i.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_qn0u4m4k">
                One diagonal = 10 cm
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_t6rwi6cr">  
                Another diagonal = 24 cm
            </p>
             <p xml:id="auto_tl3gwquw">
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Area} =  \amp \frac{1}{2 }\times d_1 \times d_2</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{2} \times 10\, \text{cm} \times 24\, \text{cm} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 120 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_vfhzbywp">
                ii. Length of One Side of the Rhombus
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_swmfnln2">
                In a rhombus, the diagonals bisect each other at 90°. That means each side of the rhombus forms a right-angled triangle with half of each diagonal.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_3qv7cequ">
                Let's find the length of one side using the Pythagorean Theorem.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_i3zbsqox">
                Each side of the rhombus is the hypotenuse of a right triangle with legs:
             </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_j28nn7wt">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Half of AC } = \amp \frac{10}{2} = 5\, \text{cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Half of BD } = \amp \frac{24}{2} = 12\, \text{cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Side} = \amp \sqrt{(5)^2 + (12)^2} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{25\,\text{cm} + 144\,\text{cm}} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{169 \,\text{cm}}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 13\,\text{cm}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    

    <example xml:id="auto_rqpngxzg">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_nklck3mb">
                A rhombus has sides of length <m>16 \; cm</m> and one of its angles is <m>60^\circ</m>. Find:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ji7v431g">
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_xfx3immt">
                        <p xml:id="auto_5n7okz0l">
                            The perpendicular height <m>h</m> of the rhombus.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_3slrgiqs">
                        <p xml:id="auto_kumtp72w">
                            The area of the rhombus (by using <m>A = s \times h</m>)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ihr0jewy">
                        <p xml:id="auto_dassft42">
                            The length of the long diagonal.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_wbcdbgkp">
                        <p xml:id="auto_opoum8qi">
                            The length of the short diagonal (remember that we also have <m>A = \frac{1}{2}\times d_1 \times d_2</m>)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="rhombus_angle">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Define rhombus vertices
                        \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (B) at (4,0);
                        \coordinate (C) at (5,3);
                        \coordinate (D) at (1,3);
                        % Draw the rhombus
                        \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;
                        % Draw one diagonal
                        \draw[dashed] (A) -- (C);
                        % Label vertices
                        \node[below left] at (A) {A};
                        \node[below right] at (B) {B};
                        \node[above right] at (C) {C};
                        \node[above left] at (D) {D};
                        % Mark angle at A
                        \draw[thick] (A) +(0.5,0) arc (0:68:0.5);
                        \node[right] at (0.3,0.6) {$60^\circ$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_ub96f9gw">
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_ohunzse0">
                        <p xml:id="auto_nb1aqpha">
                            We drop a perpendicular to <m>AB</m> at <m>D</m> to create <m>DE</m>, which has lenght <m>h</m>:
                        </p>
                        <image width="50%">
                        <latex-image label="rhombus_angle2">
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                % Define rhombus vertices
                                \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                                \coordinate (B) at (4,0);
                                \coordinate (C) at (5,3);
                                \coordinate (D) at (1,3);
                                \coordinate (E) at (1,0);
                                % Draw the rhombus
                                \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;
                                % Perpendicular
                                \draw (D) -- (E) node[midway, right] {$h$} ;
                                % Draw one diagonal
                                \draw[dashed] (A) -- (C);
                                % Label vertices
                                \node[below left] at (A) {A};
                                \node[below right] at (B) {B};
                                \node[above right] at (C) {C};
                                \node[above left] at (D) {D};
                                \node[below] at (E) {E};
                                % Mark angle at A
                                \draw[thick] (A) +(0.5,0) arc (0:68:0.5);
                                \node[right] at (0.3,0.6) {$60^\circ$};
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                        </image>
                        <p xml:id="auto_r1ibvog0">
                            Given that <m>AD = 16</m> cm, we can use trigonometry to get:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\sin 60^\circ \amp = \frac{h}{AD} </mrow>
                                <mrow>h \amp = 16 \times \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = 8\sqrt{3} \text{ cm}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_a6lb1ktm">
                        <p xml:id="auto_a3fnqkf5">
                            As <m>A = s \times h</m>, we have <m>A = 16 \times 8 \sqrt{3} = 128\sqrt{3}\text{ cm}^2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_0iz08e0y">
                        <p xml:id="auto_k361mc9m">
                            We can move the perpendicular to <m>C</m> to get another right-angled triangle:
                            <image width="50%">
                        <latex-image label="rhombus_angle3">
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                % Define rhombus vertices
                                \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                                \coordinate (B) at (4,0);
                                \coordinate (C) at (5,3);
                                \coordinate (D) at (1,3);
                                \coordinate (E) at (1,0);
                                \coordinate (F) at (5,0);
                                % Draw the rhombus
                                \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;
                                % Perpendicular
                                \draw (D) -- (E) node[midway, right] {$h$} ;
                                \draw (B) -- (F) -- (C) node[midway, right] {$h$} ;
                                % Draw one diagonal
                                \draw[dashed] (A) -- (C);
                                % Label vertices
                                \node[below left] at (A) {A};
                                \node[below] at (B) {B};
                                \node[above right] at (C) {C};
                                \node[above left] at (D) {D};
                                \node[below] at (E) {E};
                                \node[below right] at (F) {F};
                                % Mark angle at A
                                \draw[thick] (A) +(0.5,0) arc (0:34:0.5);
                                \node[right] at (0.3,0.6) {$30^\circ$};
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                        </image>
                            As discussed in the Key Takeaway, the diagonals of a rhombus bisect the angles, so we have a <m>30^\circ</m> angle, and so:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\sin 30^\circ \amp = \frac{CF}{AC} </mrow>
                                <mrow>AC \amp = \frac{h}{\frac{1}{2}}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = 16 \sqrt{3} \text{ cm}</mrow>
                            </md>
                            Thus the long diagonal <m>AC</m> has length <m>16 \sqrt{3} \text{ cm}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_6voq1qoo">
                        <p xml:id="auto_tgg2mmat">
                            Since <m>AC</m> and <m>BD</m> are the diagonals, we can use the results from (b) and (c) to get:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>A \amp = \frac{1}{2} \times AC \times BD </mrow>
                                <mrow>128\sqrt{3} \amp = \frac{1}{2} \times 16 \sqrt{3} \times BD </mrow>
                                <mrow>BD \amp = 16 \text{ cm} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment — Exit Ticket</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_ge8zw2um">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_2osq7w9y">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_o0r8zbyl">
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_0t9e2u5m">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_ubzb03ka">
                    To formatively assess individual learner understanding.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_um2kskc1">
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_ykvnboe0">
                    Learners independently complete a short assessment task (select from the exercises below).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_xdi524r9">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_df4o53o1">
                    Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge learner understanding and identify common misconceptions.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-checkpoint.ptx" />
        <exercise xml:id="ex-calculating-the-area-of-a-rhombus-given-the-height-and-base">
        <stack label="stk-calculating-the-area-of-a-rhombus-given-the-height-and-base" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-5-Area-of-Polygons/Area-of-a-rhombus/Calculating-the-area-of-a-rhombus,-given-the-height-and-base.xml"/>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-calculating-the-area-of-a-rhombus">
        <stack label="stk-calculating-the-area-of-a-rhombus" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-5-Area-of-Polygons/Area-of-a-rhombus/Calculating-the-area-of-a-rhombus.xml"/>
    </exercise>




    <exercises xml:id="exercises-area-of-rhombuses">
        <title>Exercises</title>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-rhombus-diagonals-16-30">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_s3rfyi0t">
                    A rhombus has diagonals measuring 16 cm and 30 cm.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_zikzxi42">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_pbs42eog">
                            <p xml:id="auto_urrj4ra8">Find the area of the rhombus.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_4jofmwic">
                            <p xml:id="auto_8kcjyt3h">Find the side length of the rhombus.</p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_ne71bmjr">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_mfj7wlqy">
                            <p xml:id="auto_t8shagyd">
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\text{Area} \amp = \frac{1}{2} \times d_1 \times d_2</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2} \times 16 \times 30</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = 240 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_b97xnm9r">
                            <p xml:id="auto_15keamj7">
                                The diagonals of a rhombus bisect each other at right angles. The half diagonals are <m>8</m> cm and <m>15</m> cm.
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\text{Side} \amp = \sqrt{8^2 + 15^2}</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{64 + 225}</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{289}</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = 17 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-rhombus-road-sign">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_3s2w69br">
                    A diamond-shaped road sign is a rhombus with a diagonal of 40 cm and another diagonal of 60 cm. Find:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_wm1e8m1u">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_3jloktea">
                            <p xml:id="auto_39zmdow1">The area of the sign.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_i7mxvojt">
                            <p xml:id="auto_t4r2xeo8">The length of one side of the sign.</p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_isxvutge">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_a2aajppt">
                            <p xml:id="auto_ucbrxaek">
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\text{Area} \amp = \frac{1}{2} \times d_1 \times d_2</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2} \times 40 \times 60</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = 1{,}200 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_8fzol78x">
                            <p xml:id="auto_07z15aav">
                                The half diagonals are <m>20</m> cm and <m>30</m> cm.
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\text{Side} \amp = \sqrt{20^2 + 30^2}</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{400 + 900}</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = \sqrt{1300}</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp \approx 36.06 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-rhombus-perimeter-48">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_y5ta4dtk">
                    The perimeter of a rhombus is 48 cm. Find the length of one side.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_pmub6ihl">
                    Since all four sides of a rhombus are equal:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Side} \amp = \frac{\text{Perimeter}}{4}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \frac{48}{4}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 12 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-rhombus-car-logo">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_bg3n874m">
                    A car logo is shaped like a rhombus. The diagonals measure 14 cm and 10 cm. Find its area.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_9fvv96rx">
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Area} \amp = \frac{1}{2} \times d_1 \times d_2</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2} \times 14 \times 10</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 70 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-rhombus-angles-60">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_5qf4h53u">
                    A rhombus has one of its angles measuring <m>60°</m>. Find the other three angles.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_b6midtll">
                    In a rhombus, opposite angles are equal and consecutive angles are supplementary (sum to <m>180^\circ</m>).
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_2hdj9ckg">
                    The angle opposite to <m>60°</m> is also <m>60°</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_nphm997h">
                    Each of the other two angles is <m>180° - 60° = 120°</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_7jtv6yx0">
                    Therefore the four angles are: <m>60°, \; 120°, \; 60°, \; 120°</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-rhombus-tiling">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_enwymrph">
                    A tiling design on a floor is made of rhombus-shaped tiles. Each tile has diagonals of 18 cm and 24 cm.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_7d2bdpob">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_4carynzk">
                            <p xml:id="auto_a6gdz22v">Find the area of one tile.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_bn55j45x">
                            <p xml:id="auto_hrhbiceg">If 20 such tiles cover a portion of the floor, what is the total area covered?</p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_m5ul741m">
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_zjbk0do5">
                            <p xml:id="auto_wx4mae2u">
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\text{Area of one tile} \amp = \frac{1}{2} \times d_1 \times d_2</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2} \times 18 \times 24</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = 216 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_963xcgv3">
                            <p xml:id="auto_h0jhq0af">
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\text{Total area} \amp = 20 \times 216</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = 4{,}320 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table xml:id="auto_4eh4yhsl">
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Provide pre-drawn rhombuses with diagonals already marked. Use simpler numbers for diagonal lengths. Pair struggling students with confident problem solvers. Provide step-by-step calculation templates. Allow use of calculators.</line>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>Encourage students to draw their own rhombuses from word problems. Ask students to explain which formula they chose and why. Provide mixed practice with both finding area and finding side lengths.</line>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert> Challenge students to derive the formula themselves using the properties of diagonals. Explore real-world applications: architecture, design, tiling patterns. Investigate the relationship between the area of a rhombus and the area of a square. Apply the formula to find missing diagonal lengths when area is known.</line>
                    </cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Extension Activity: Designing Rhombus-Shaped Patterns</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_0n1291cj">
                Students work in groups to design a rhombus-shaped pattern (tiling, logo, playing card design) and calculate its area. They draw the rhombus on graph paper with appropriate dimensions, measure or specify the lengths of both diagonals, calculate the area using the formula, and if needed, calculate the side length using the Pythagorean theorem. Students present their findings to the class.
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

